If you doubt feminism, or hold tightly to traditional masculine ideals, this book is worth a read. If you think you’re past “toxic masculinity” read this book. I thought I was, and learned so much about new ways I can support myself and other men along the way to health.

Author: Marvin Harris
My Review: A fascinating read that skids to the end with an underdeveloped diatribe against the “counter-culture”. Harris spends the whole book diving into the material causes of strange phenomena, then writes the counterculture off as stupid and ungrateful without considering what material causes might underly the movement. It’s not that I disagree with some of the points made about the 60’s counterculture, it is the fact that Harris’s final points are underdeveloped in contrast to the rest of his book and lacking the restraint and measured understanding of the rest of his book.

Title: Apocalypse Never: Why Environmental Alarmism Hurts Us All
Author: Michael Shellenberger
My Review:
While I'm not impressed with the science (Vaclov Smil is a much better choice to learn about energy + agriculture), I do think Shellenberger presents worrying conflicts of interest among many environmentalists. This book is a sober reminder that anyone can become bigoted. It has inspired me to look deeper into the issues and take less at face value, including this book.

After further reflection, I'm going to go further and say this book is not scientifically rigorous. While it makes interesting points, there is lots of laziness. An example is Shellenberger's assertion that rising levels of anxiety among younger generations are a direct cause of environmental alarmism. While I won't rule it out, it's far from the only factor at play (cough, cough, Social Media) and at the very least a vast oversimplification.

Title: Thomas Merton: Spiritual Direction And Meditation
Author: Thomas Merton
My Review: Oddly no nonsense take on faith for a Catholic monk. I expected more flowery language and self-laceration but Merton's directions are simple, clear, and doable (if not easy). He is fully aware that we are all human yet also fully believes we can be something more than that through an intentional connection to the divine.
